{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.04,0.05,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9893"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54827"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3851"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44810"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent due to three weeks of tiredness, poor appetite, and abdominal swelling. His parent has also noticed dark circles under his eyes. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired but not acutely unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended with a firm, non-tender mass in the left upper quadrant crossing the midline. There is no hepatomegaly. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood tests show haemoglobin 92 g/L (105-135), white cell count 8.2 x 10^9/L (5-15), platelets 350 x 10^9/L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Serum alpha-fetoprotein","Urinary protein electrophoresis","Positron emission tomography scan","Bone marrow aspiration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features suggestive of neuroblastoma, including constitutional symptoms, periorbital ecchymoses (\u0027raccoon eyes\u0027), and an abdominal mass. The age of presentation and location of the mass are typical for neuroblastoma, which most commonly arises from the adrenal glands or sympathetic chain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial imaging investigation for a child with a suspected abdominal mass. It is readily available, does not involve radiation, and can usually be performed without sedation. Ultrasound can characterise the mass, determine its relationship to surrounding structures, and guide further imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E may be required for staging if neuroblastoma is confirmed, but it is not the appropriate first investigation. It would be performed after initial imaging confirms the presence of a mass consistent with neuroblastoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for staging and monitoring response to treatment but is not the initial investigation of choice. It involves radiation exposure and usually requires sedation in young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is not helpful in diagnosing neuroblastoma. While urinary catecholamines (vanillylmandelic acid and homovanillic acid) are useful markers for neuroblastoma, these would be ordered after initial imaging suggests the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum alpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour marker more commonly associated with hepatoblastoma or germ cell tumours rather than neuroblastoma. The clinical presentation is not typical for these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter ultrasound confirms a mass suspicious for neuroblastoma, further workup would include CT or MRI for staging, urinary catecholamines, and metaiodobenzylguanidine (MIBG) scan to assess for metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuroblastoma commonly presents with an abdominal mass and constitutional symptoms in children under 5 years of age.","Elevated urinary catecholamines (VMA/HVA) are characteristic of neuroblastoma.","Initial imaging for suspected neuroblastoma should include abdominal ultrasound followed by CT/MRI for staging."],"references":["Matthay KK, Maris JM, Schleiermacher G, Nakagawara A, Mackall CL, Diller L, et al. Neuroblastoma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Nov 10;2(1):1\u201321."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54827"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54827","lin